---

<Layout title="Ch.4 — Logistic Regression" favicon="🤖">
  <main>

    <a href="/reading/machine-learning/" class="text-sm mb-4 inline-block">&larr; back to machine learning</a>

    <h1>Logistic Regression</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Deisenroth et al., <em>Mathematics for Machine Learning</em> (CC BY 4.0) &middot; <a href="https://mml-book.github.io/">mml-book.github.io</a></p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">Logistic regression squashes linear output through a <strong>sigmoid</strong> to get probabilities. <strong>Cross-entropy loss</strong> measures how wrong the probabilities are &mdash; it penalizes confident wrong answers heavily. <strong>Maximum likelihood</strong> estimation is equivalent to minimizing cross-entropy. The decision boundary is where the probability hits 0.5.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- SVG: interactive sigmoid curve -->
    <div class="flex flex-col items-center my-6">
      <svg id="sig-svg" viewBox="0 0 360 220" class="w-full max-w-sm" style="font-family: ui-monospace, monospace;">
        <!-- Axes -->
        <line x1="30" y1="170" x2="330" y2="170" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1" stroke-opacity="0.3"/>
        <line x1="180" y1="180" x2="180" y2="15" stroke="#71717a" stroke-width="1" stroke-opacity="0.45"/>
        <text x="335" y="174" fill="currentColor" font-size="10" fill-opacity="0.4">z</text>
        <text x="175" y="12" fill="currentColor" font-size="10" fill-opacity="0.4">&sigma;</text>
        <!-- Asymptote lines -->
        <line x1="30" y1="30" x2="330" y2="30" stroke="#71717a" stroke-width="0.5" stroke-opacity="0.45" stroke-dasharray="4,4"/>
        <text x="335" y="34" fill="currentColor" font-size="9" fill-opacity="0.3">1</text>
        <text x="335" y="174" fill="currentColor" font-size="9" fill-opacity="0.3">0</text>
        <!-- Sigmoid curve (computed polyline) -->
        <polyline id="sig-curve" fill="none" stroke="#60a5fa" stroke-width="2" stroke-opacity="0.6"/>
        <!-- Dynamic elements -->
        <line id="sig-vline" stroke="#f59e0b" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-opacity="0.4" stroke-dasharray="3,3"/>
        <line id="sig-hline" stroke="#f59e0b" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-opacity="0.4" stroke-dasharray="3,3"/>
        <circle id="sig-dot" r="4" fill="#f59e0b" fill-opacity="0.8"/>
        <!-- Class labels -->
        <text x="100" y="155" text-anchor="middle" fill="#a78bfa" font-size="10" fill-opacity="0.5">class 0</text>
        <text x="260" y="55" text-anchor="middle" fill="#34d399" font-size="10" fill-opacity="0.5">class 1</text>
        <!-- Readout -->
        <text id="sig-readout" x="180" y="210" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="11" fill-opacity="0.7"></text>
      </svg>
      <input id="sig-slider" type="range" min="-60" max="60" value="0" step="1" class="w-full max-w-sm mt-2" style="accent-color: #60a5fa;" />
    </div>
    <script is:inline>
    (function() {
      var LEFT = 30, RIGHT = 330, TOP = 30, BOT = 170;
      var ZMIN = -6, ZMAX = 6;
      function sigmoid(z) { return 1 / (1 + Math.exp(-z)); }
      function zToX(z) { return LEFT + (z - ZMIN) / (ZMAX - ZMIN) * (RIGHT - LEFT); }
      function sigToY(s) { return BOT - s * (BOT - TOP); }

      // Draw static curve
      var pts = [];
      for (var i = -60; i <= 60; i++) {
        var z = i / 10;
        pts.push(zToX(z).toFixed(1) + "," + sigToY(sigmoid(z)).toFixed(1));
      }
      document.getElementById("sig-curve").setAttribute("points", pts.join(" "));

      var slider = document.getElementById("sig-slider");
      var dot = document.getElementById("sig-dot");
      var vline = document.getElementById("sig-vline");
      var hline = document.getElementById("sig-hline");
      var readout = document.getElementById("sig-readout");

      function update() {
        var z = slider.value / 10;
        var s = sigmoid(z);
        var cx = zToX(z), cy = sigToY(s);
        dot.setAttribute("cx", cx);
        dot.setAttribute("cy", cy);
        vline.setAttribute("x1", cx); vline.setAttribute("y1", cy);
        vline.setAttribute("x2", cx); vline.setAttribute("y2", BOT);
        hline.setAttribute("x1", LEFT); hline.setAttribute("y1", cy);
        hline.setAttribute("x2", cx); hline.setAttribute("y2", cy);
        var cls = s >= 0.5 ? 1 : 0;
        readout.textContent = "z = " + z.toFixed(1) + " → σ(z) = " + s.toFixed(2) + " → class " + cls;
      }
      slider.addEventListener("input", update);
      update();
    })();
    </script>

    <!-- 1. Sigmoid function -->
    <h3>Sigmoid function</h3>
    <p>The sigmoid &sigma;(z) = 1 / (1 + e&#x207B;&#x1DBB;) maps any real number to (0, 1). Large positive inputs map near 1; large negative inputs map near 0. At z = 0, &sigma;(0) = 0.5.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Sigmoid function: sigma(z) = 1 / (1 + e^(-z))

(define (sigmoid z)
  (/ 1 (+ 1 (exp (- z)))))

; Test at key points
(display "sigmoid(-5) = ") (display (sigmoid -5)) (newline)
(display "sigmoid(-1) = ") (display (sigmoid -1)) (newline)
(display "sigmoid(0)  = ") (display (sigmoid 0)) (newline)
(display "sigmoid(1)  = ") (display (sigmoid 1)) (newline)
(display "sigmoid(5)  = ") (display (sigmoid 5)) (newline)

; Key property: sigma(-z) = 1 - sigma(z)
(display "sigmoid(2) + sigmoid(-2) = ")
(display (+ (sigmoid 2) (sigmoid -2)))
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`# Sigmoid function
import math

def sigmoid(z):
    return 1 / (1 + math.exp(-z))

for z in [-5, -1, 0, 1, 5]:
    print("sigmoid({}) = {:.4f}".format(z, sigmoid(z)))

# Key property: sigma(-z) = 1 - sigma(z)
print("sigmoid(2) + sigmoid(-2) =", sigmoid(2) + sigmoid(-2))
`} />
    </div>

    <!-- 2. Cross-entropy loss -->
    <h3>Cross-entropy loss</h3>
    <p>Cross-entropy measures the distance between the true label distribution and the predicted probabilities. For binary classification: L = -[y log(p) + (1-y) log(1-p)]. When the model is confident and <em>right</em>, loss is low. When confident and <em>wrong</em>, loss explodes.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Cross-entropy loss for binary classification
; L = -[y * log(p) + (1-y) * log(1-p)]

(define (cross-entropy y p)
  (- (+ (* y (log p))
        (* (- 1 y) (log (- 1 p))))))

; When model is right (y=1, p close to 1)
(display "y=1, p=0.9:  L = ") (display (cross-entropy 1 0.9)) (newline)
(display "y=1, p=0.99: L = ") (display (cross-entropy 1 0.99)) (newline)

; When model is wrong (y=1, p close to 0)
(display "y=1, p=0.5:  L = ") (display (cross-entropy 1 0.5)) (newline)
(display "y=1, p=0.1:  L = ") (display (cross-entropy 1 0.1)) (newline)
(display "y=1, p=0.01: L = ") (display (cross-entropy 1 0.01)) (newline)

; Confident and wrong is heavily penalized
(display "y=0, p=0.99: L = ") (display (cross-entropy 0 0.99))
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`# Cross-entropy loss
import math

def cross_entropy(y, p):
    return -(y * math.log(p) + (1 - y) * math.log(1 - p))

# Right answers: low loss
print("y=1, p=0.9:  L =", round(cross_entropy(1, 0.9), 4))
print("y=1, p=0.99: L =", round(cross_entropy(1, 0.99), 4))

# Wrong answers: high loss
print("y=1, p=0.5:  L =", round(cross_entropy(1, 0.5), 4))
print("y=1, p=0.1:  L =", round(cross_entropy(1, 0.1), 4))
print("y=1, p=0.01: L =", round(cross_entropy(1, 0.01), 4))

# Confident and wrong: catastrophic
print("y=0, p=0.99: L =", round(cross_entropy(0, 0.99), 4))
`} />
    </div>

    <!-- 3. Gradient descent for logistic regression -->
    <h3>Gradient descent for logistic regression</h3>
    <p>The gradient of cross-entropy loss with respect to the weight is (p - y) &middot; x. Same update rule as linear regression, but p comes from the sigmoid. This elegance is not a coincidence &mdash; it falls out of the exponential family.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Logistic regression via gradient descent
; Dataset: (x, label) — 1D for clarity

(define data '((1 0) (2 0) (3 0) (4 0)
               (6 1) (7 1) (8 1) (9 1)))
(define n (length data))
(define lr 0.1)

(define (sigmoid z) (/ 1 (+ 1 (exp (- z)))))

(define (train w b steps)
  (if (= steps 0)
      (begin
        (display "w = ") (display w) (newline)
        (display "b = ") (display b) (newline)
        ; Show predictions
        (display "Predictions:") (newline)
        (for-each
          (lambda (point)
            (let ((x (car point))
                  (y (cadr point))
                  (p (sigmoid (+ (* w (car point)) b))))
              (display "  x=") (display x)
              (display " true=") (display y)
              (display " pred=") (display p) (newline)))
          data))
      (let* ((preds (map (lambda (pt)
                           (sigmoid (+ (* w (car pt)) b)))
                         data))
             (labels (map cadr data))
             (errors (map - preds labels))
             (xs (map car data))
             (dw (/ (apply + (map * errors xs)) n))
             (db (/ (apply + errors) n)))
        (train (- w (* lr dw))
               (- b (* lr db))
               (- steps 1)))))

(display "Logistic regression on 1D data") (newline)
(train 0 0 200)
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`# Logistic regression via gradient descent
import math

data = [(1,0), (2,0), (3,0), (4,0),
        (6,1), (7,1), (8,1), (9,1)]
n = len(data)
lr = 0.1

def sigmoid(z):
    return 1 / (1 + math.exp(-z))

w, b = 0.0, 0.0
for step in range(200):
    preds = [sigmoid(w * x + b) for x, y in data]
    labels = [y for x, y in data]
    errors = [p - y for p, y in zip(preds, labels)]
    xs = [x for x, y in data]
    dw = sum(e * x for e, x in zip(errors, xs)) / n
    db = sum(errors) / n
    w -= lr * dw
    b -= lr * db

print("w =", round(w, 4))
print("b =", round(b, 4))
print("Predictions:")
for x, y in data:
    p = sigmoid(w * x + b)
    print("  x={} true={} pred={:.3f}".format(x, y, p))
`} />
    </div>

